<h2>How to do kW to kWh Calculation Yourself</h2>
<p>Having to convert and calculate specific solar measures can be difficult=
. Thankfully, this isn=E2=80=99t true of converting kilowatts (kW) to kilow=
att hours (kWh). Solar beginners often encounter difficulties with these ca=
lculations and aren=E2=80=99t provided with the correct guidance to make th=
ese calculations easier.</p>
<p>The truth is that many of these solar calculations and conversions are o=
vercomplicated with unnecessary solar jargon and intricate equations. The i=
nternet is littered with impressive and powerful online solar calculators w=
hich include, <a href=3D"https://shopsolarkits.com/blogs/learning-center/kw=
h-per-square-foot-calculator" target=3D"_blank">kWh per square foot calcula=
tors</a>, <a href=3D"https://shopsolarkits.com/blogs/learning-center/kilowa=
tt-hour-cost-calculator" target=3D"_blank">kWh cost calculators</a>, and st=
andard <a href=3D"https://shopsolarkits.com/blogs/learning-center/kwh-calcu=
lator" target=3D"_blank">kilowatt usage calculators</a>.</p>
<p>To make things simple, we want to take you through a basic kW to kWh cal=
culator, why you need it, and exactly what each of those terms in the equat=
ion represents. Our solution uses a straightforward formula that can be use=
d to quickly translate these two measurements, free of any overly intricate=
 math.</p>
<h2>The Difference Between kW and kWh</h2>
<p><span>Because the terms kilowatt-hour (kWh) and kilowatt (kW) sound simi=
lar, they=E2=80=99re often confused which can make understanding what each =
represents difficult. In truth, these two variables are inextricably linked=
. What happens to one of the values will affect the other.</span></p>
<p><span>The key distinction between the two is that kWh measures total ele=
ctricity usage over time, while kW measures the rate of electricity usage.<=
/span></p>
<p><span>Although the terms power and energy are frequently misused interch=
angeably, technically speaking, a kWh is a measurement of energy, whereas a=
 kW is a measurement of power.</span></p>
<h3><span>Why Is kWh Important?</span></h3>
<p><span>To put it in perspective, a kilowatt is equivalent to 1,000 watts.=
 It measures how much power electrical equipment uses or produces.</span></=
p>
<p><span>On the other hand, a kilowatt-hour measures the energy consumption=
 of an electrical device every hour. This is particularly important for wor=
king out energy costs for the month or even the entire year.</span></p>
<p><span>If you use a kettle that uses 2,000 watts of energy for five minut=
es, you need to calculate that as a fraction of an hour.</span></p>
<p><span>In this case:</span></p>
<p><b>kWh =3D 2 x (5/60)</b></p>
<p><b>kWh =3D 0.17 kWh</b></p>
<p><span>Let=E2=80=99s say you have a daily household kilowatt-hour usage o=
f 5 kWh. You can use this number to determine how much money you spend on e=
lectricity by using your local utility rates.</span></p>
<p><span>All you have to do is first multiply your average kilowatt-hour us=
age by 30 days to get your monthly consumption=E2=80=94in this case, the re=
sult is 150 kWh per month. Next, take your local electricity rate per kWh a=
nd multiply it by your monthly usage.</span></p>
<p><span>For this example, we can use the national average rate of $0.16 pe=
r kWh. Take your 150 kWh and multiply it by the $0.16 and you have a monthl=
y rate of $24. Realistically, your household usage is likely to be higher t=
han this, but the same rules apply.</span></p>
<h2 id=3D"how-to-convert-between-kw-and-kwh"><span>kW and kWh Calculator - =
How to Convert</span></h2>
<p><span>Instead of scouring the internet in search of an online kW to kWh =
converter that isn=E2=80=99t accurate and doesn=E2=80=99t show you the step=
s, you can use our formula that only involves two key electrical metrics.</=
span></p>
<p><span>Often your solar panel guide displays the following formula in a c=
omplicated way, but it=E2=80=99s much simpler than what these manuals portr=
ay.</span></p>
<p><span>The one in solar manuals will read as follows:</span></p>
<p><b>E</b><b>(kWh)</b><b><span>&nbsp;</span>=3D P</b><b>(kW)</b><b><span>&=
nbsp;</span>X T</b><b>(hrs)</b></p>
<p><span>These letters (E for energy, P for power, and T for time) along wi=
th their subscripts (kWh, kW, and hrs) tend to confuse new solar owners whi=
ch means you might end up making careless mistakes.</span></p>
<p><span>To make this formula easier to read, all you have to do is drop th=
e letters and let the subscripts take the subject of the formula.</span></p=
>
<p><b>kWh =3D kW X Hrs</b></p>
<p><span>This is the only formula you need to convert kW to kWh, which is m=
ore accurate than relying on an online converter.</span></p>
<h2 style=3D"letter-spacing: normal;" id=3D"how-to-convert-between-kw-and-k=
wh">kW and kWh Calculator - <span>Conversion Example</span>
</h2>
<p><span>To demonstrate how simple this formula is to use, here=E2=80=99s a=
 common example that many solar panel owners often face. First, we=E2=80=99=
re going to calculate the kWh from kW.</span></p>
<p><span>Let=E2=80=99s say we have a solar panel system that has an output =
of 20 kW running for 5 hours a day. To convert it to kWh, all we need to do=
 is substitute the given values into our simple formula.</span></p>
<p><b>kWh =3D 20 kW X 5 hrs</b></p>
<p><span>This will give us a total kWh consumption of 100 kWh.</span></p>
<p><span>You can then use this number and work out your monthly output that=
 we worked out previously. This allows us to work out the monthly output of=
 our solar system to see how much energy is given off by the panel system.<=
/span></p>
<p><span>Additionally, with our simple equation, you can&nbsp;</span><a hre=
f=3D"https://shopsolarkits.com/blogs/learning-center/convert-kwh-to-kw" tar=
get=3D"_blank">convert kWh to kW</a><span>&nbsp;</span><span>you are given =
the kWh and the amount of time a specific device is used for.</span></p>
<p><span>As an example, we have a solar system with a kWh reading of 80 kWh=
 and a running time of 4 hours. All you would need to do is substitute your=
 known values into the formula and rearrange it so that kW becomes the prim=
ary variable.</span></p>
<p><span>The new formula reads as follows:</span></p>
<p><span>kW =3D kWh/hrs</span></p>
<p><span>We simply have to substitute the 80 kWh and divide it by the hours=
 to get the kW reading. For this example, we get a final kW reading of 20 k=
W.</span></p>
<p><span>And that=E2=80=99s how easy it is to convert between kW and kWh us=
ing our simple formula.</span></p>
<h2>kW and kWh Calculator - <span>Conclusion</span>
</h2>
<p><span>Electrical conversions and calculations, especially in the solar p=
anel space, often aren=E2=80=99t as complicated as electrical manuals make =
them out to be. Once you understand the variables going into the equation, =
these calculations are surprisingly simple.</span></p>
